Article Atomic orbitals modulated dual functional bimetallic phosphides derived from MOF on MOF structure for boosting high efficient overall water splitting Bohan An a b Weilong Liu a b Jipeng Dong a b Ning Li a b Yangqin Gao a b Lei Ge a b * a State Key Laboratory of Heavy Oil Processing, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China State Key Laboratory of Heavy Oil Processing College of New Energy and Materials China University of Petroleum Beijing Beijing 102249 China State Key Laboratory of Heavy Oil Processing, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China b Department of Materials Science and Engineering, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China Department of Materials Science and Engineering College of New Energy and Materials China University of Petroleum Beijing Beijing 102249 China Department of Materials Science and Engineering, College of New Energy and Materials, China University of Petroleum Beijing, Beijing 102249, China * Corresponding author The electronic modulation characteristics of efficient metal phosphide electrocatalysts can be utilized to tune the performance of oxygen evolution reaction (OER). However, improving the overall water splitting performance remains a challenging task. By building metal organic framework (MOF) on MOF heterostructures, an efficient strategy for controlling the electrical structure of MOFs was presented in this study. ZIF-67 was in-situ synthesized on MIL-88 (Fe) using a two-step self-assembly method, followed by low-temperature phosphorization to ultimately synthesize FeP-CoP3 bimetallic phosphides. By combining atomic orbital theory and theoretical calculations (density functional theory), the results reveal the successful modulation of electronic orbitals in FeP-CoP3 bimetallic phosphides, which are synthesized from MOF on MOF structure. The synergistic impact of the metal center Co species and the phase conjugation of both kinds of MOFs are responsible for this regulatory phenomenon. Therefore, the catalyst demonstrates excellent properties, demonstrating HER 81 mV (η10) in a 1.0 mol L−1 KOH solution and OER 239 mV (η50) low overpotentials. The FeP-CoP3 linked dual electrode alkaline batteries, which are bifunctional electrocatalysts, have a good electrocatalytic ability and may last for 50 h. They require just 1.49 V (η50) for total water breakdown. Through this technique, the electrical structure of electrocatalysts may be altered to increase catalytic activity. Graphical Abstract By building metal organic framework MOF on MOF heterostructures, followed by low-temperature phosphorization technology, FeP-CoP3 bimetallic phosphides are ultimately synthesized. FeP-CoP3 material is a bifunctional electrocatalyst with a good electrocatalytic ability and may last for 50 h. They require just 1.49 V (η50) for total water breakdown. Keywords Transition metal phosphides MOF on MOF Atomic orbital theory Density functional theory calculation 1 Introduction Facing with the current global energy and carbon emissions issues, hydrogen fuel is considered the most effective method to traditional energy due to its high calorific value and zero carbon emissions [1–3]. Among them, the use of green hydrogen produced by electrochemical water decomposition is currently recognized as the most environmentally and friendly method [4–6]. However, electrochemical hydrogen evolution requires two and a half reactions (hydrogen evolution reaction and oxygen evolution reaction) to occur simultaneously, and the slow kinetics of oxygen evolution reaction (OER) significantly hinder energy conversion efficiency, which is the result of the four-step proton coupled electron transfer process [7–10]. Adding noble metal-based materials such as Pt, IrO2, and RuO2 to the electrode has always been the preferred solution to enhance the progress of this semi reaction [11]. However, their extremely precious resource reserves limit prevailing application, and its high market price further suppresses its widespread promotion. Therefore, exploring non-precious metal electrocatalysts with high activity and stability is crucial [12–14]. As a substitute for precious metal catalysts, transition metal-based catalysts not only have large natural reserves and low market prices, but also possess excellent electrochemical performance and stability [3]. So they can be used as workable substitutes for efficient hydrogen generation. In electrocatalytic processes, transition metal oxides (TMO) demonstrate exceptional OER stability and performance [15]. However, due to their poor HER performance in complete hydrolysis, the application range is often limited (often used as a semi reaction catalyst). Moreover, transition metal phosphides (TMPs) present exceptional performance in fully hydrolyzed water, while their use is often limited due to their weak stability [16]. Therefore, by utilizing appropriate skeleton structures and combining the advantages of various architectures, multifunctional electrocatalysts can be developed. Because of their rich porosity, large surface areas, movable structures and plenty of active sites, metal organic frameworks (MOFs) have a lot of potential applications in the field of electrocatalysis [17]. Further, by modifying the metal centers and organic ligands, MOFs’ electronic structure can be precisely controlled. This is important because the electronic structure of MOFs has a significant impact on the OER performance by altering the binding energy between the electrocatalyst and reaction intermediates during the process. Moreover, the construction of multi metal MOFs provides a new approach for electronic structure modulation [18,19]. Notably, the synergistic interaction between Co and Fe ions causes CoFe MOF to exhibit modest electronic structural adjustment, increasing catalytic activity and making it one of the most efficient OER electrocatalysts [20]. For example, Liu et al. [21] firstly synthesized the core using MOF templating method, and then obtained the outer shell, finally prepared CoP nanoparticles containing within the CoFeP shell. This catalyst showed excellent OER performance in alkaline media with an overpotential of 266 mV (η10). It outperformed commercial RuO2 and CoFeP nanocubes in terms of performance. The encapsulation structure of CoP/CoFeP was shown to have a rich Fe doped shell through theoretical calculations and experimental characterization. This phenomenon allows for electronic interactions between CoP and CoFeP, exposing more active sites and ultimately improving OER performance. Jiang et al. [22] adjusted the electronic structure of MOFs by constructing MOF on MOF heterostructures. MOF-(74+274)@NFF was prepared on NiFe substrate by two-step self-assembly technology. This material also presented excellent OER performance with 198 and 223 mV (η10) in 1.0 and 0.1 mol L−1 KOH solutions, nevertheless the HER activity is insufficient. Therefore, creating dual MOF hybrids is a useful tactic for enhancing MOF catalytic activity and adjusting their electronic structure. By converting two different MOF structures into a mixed catalyst to maintain their respective characteristics and advantages that a single MOF cannot provide, can be utilized to develop high performance electrocatalysts. So far, numerous conjugated MOF-based compounds with exceptional OER performance have been investigated as electrocatalysts [18–22]. However, the inherent electron transfer mechanism of MOF on MOF hybrids remains ambiguous, which poses a challenge for designing efficient electrocatalysts [23–26]. In this work, bimetallic phosphides were reasonably designed and synthesized from MOF on MOF structure to achieve precise charge modulation and synergistic effects of electron redistribution. The bimetallic center leads to an improvement in performance. Specifically, through a two-step solvent thermal epitaxial growth process, MIL-88(Fe)@ZIF-67 precursor with MOF on MOF structure was obtained. Finally, bimetallic phosphides were generated through in-situ phosphating process. The phase conjugation of two types of MOFs and the synergistic effect of metal centers have a tuning effect on the electron distribution. Its larger specific surface area exposes more active sites. It is worth noting that the heterojunction interface generated between FeP and CoP3 promotes electron transfer, enriches active sites and regulates electronic structure, thereby achieving excellent electrocatalytic performance, which is far superior to phosphides synthesized by a single MOF precursor. Detailed investigation and theoretical calculation results imply that the synergistic effect between Co and Fe ions can reduce the energy barrier of the rate determination step (RDS), thereby improving ability and reducing the activation energy (E a). 2 Experimental 2.1 Synthesis All compounds are purchased and used directly without additional purification. Firstly, 20 mmol (2.32g) fumaric acid and 10 mmol (4.04g) of Fe(NO3)3·9H2O were added and rapidly stirred in a 1:1 volume ratio ethanol water mixture, and mixture was maintained for 24 h. The reddish brown precipitate was collected by centrifugation, and then dried at 70 °C for 12 h. By changing the content of malic acid while remaining unchanged, the size of MIL-88(Fe) can be regulated. The as-prepared MIL-88(Fe) was added into 50 mL methanol solution, 4 mmol 2-methylimidazole was dropped and stirred for 30 min, and then 1 mmol Co(NO3)2·6H2O was added to form a mixed solution. The merged solution was kept at room temperature for 24 h. After the solution is fully dispersed, the purple substance was collected by centrifugation, and then dried at 70 °C for 12 h. Finally, MIL-88(Fe)@ZIF-67 precursor was obtained. NaH2PO2·H2O (located on the upstream side) and MIL-88(Fe)@ZIF-67 precursor are placed in pipeline equipment with 1:10 ratio. Experimental phosphating conditions: under continuous nitrogen protection, the temperature is maintained at 400 °C, the heating rate is 2 °C min−1, and the insulation time is 2 h. Finally, the product was wash repeatedly with an alcohol solution to remove unreacted substances and impurities. Finally, the samples were dried overnight to get the target catalysts FeP and CoP3, which was labeled as FeP-CoP3 for subsequent expression convenience (Fig. S1). The synthesis process of other catalyzers is described in the supporting information. The scanning electron microscope (SEM) images of comparison samples FeP and CoP3 are shown in Fig. S2. 2.2 Characterizations The crystallographic characterization of all samples was investigated by X-ray diffractometer (XRD) (Cu-Kα radiation, λ = 1.5406 Å) with a 2θ range of 10° to 90° and a scan rate of 5°min−1. Morphological characterization of the electrodes was carried out by using a FEI Quanta 200 F emission SEM with an accelerating voltage of 20 kV. The morphologies of the catalysts were a−1nalyzed by FEI Tecnai G2 F20 transmission electron microscope (TEM) and HRTEM imaging. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) measurements were performed on a spectrometer PHI 5300 ESCA, using a Mg Kα monochromator calibrated with the C 1s peak (284.8 eV) to provide incident photon energy. In addition, the electrodes were also carried out on a Raman spectrometer (λ = 532 nm). 2.3 Electrochemical testing conditions Electrochemical measurements were tested in a standard three-electrode system (CHI660E, China) in KOH (1.0 mol L−1). The carbon rod and saturated calomel served as the counter electrode and reference electrode, respectively, while the working electrode was 1 × 1 cm2 FTO loaded with electrocatalyst. High purity N2 gas was pumped for 30 min prior to eliminating dissolved O2. Linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) measurements were performed in KOH (1.0 mol L−1, pH = 13.8) electrolyte at 5 mV s−1 with iR compensation. The HER and OER potentials were converted to reversible hydrogen electrode (RHE) according to the Eqs. (1) and (2): (1) η(HER) = E(Ag/AgCl) + 0.0591 × PH + 0.2415 (2) η(OER) = E(Hg/AgCl) + 0.0591 × PH + 0.2415–1.23 The Tafel slope (b) is derived from η = a + blog(j), where j represents the current density. The electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS) was conducted at 5 mV (vs. RHE) for HER in the frequency range of 105 to 10−1 Hz. Electrochemical surface area (ECSA) was used to record cyclic voltammogry (CV) at 20, 40, 60, 80, 100, and 120 mV s−1. Catalytic performance towards overall water splitting was tested in a two-electrode system, and LSV maps were recorded at 10 mV s−1 using V-CoFeP as the anode and cathode. E(RHE) = E(Ag/AgCl) + 0.059 × pH + 0.197 V 2.4 Calculation of density functional theory (DFT) The calculation method is a theoretical analysis way depended on DFT, using VASP (Vienna Ab initio Simulation Package) package and Projector Augmented Wave (PAW) method. Perdew Bourke Ernzerhof (PBE) and Generalized Gradient Approximation (GGA) is adopted for the swap-related multi-function. Because of the correlated electron effect in transition metals, GGA approximation cannot exactly explain the electronic structure and mechanization of magnetism, so the GGA+U (Hubbard parameter) method with Hubbard correction is adopted. The synthesis process, characterization methods, electrochemical measurements and DFT calculations of other TMPs are fully illustrated in the supporting information. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Characterization of prepared sample As shown in TEM images and SEM images (Fig. 1(a) and Fig. S3), it can be noticed that the FeP-CoP3 sample is composed of two types of nanoparticles. These nanoparticles are tightly constructed together through the MOF on MOF method, and a large number of electrochemical active sites are exposed on their surface (Fig. 1(b)). Furthermore, selected area electron diffraction (SAED) patterns relative to lattice points (Fig. 1(f)) can be observed with spacings corresponding to the (011), (020), and (111) planes of shuttle shaped FeP and the (321) and (013) planes of hexagonal CoP3, further confirming the synthesis of the target product (Figs. 1(c)–(e)). It can also be found that there are a large number of heterojunction structures at the junction of the two types of nanoparticles. Moreover, the results of TEM Energy Dispersion Spectroscopy (TEM EDS) confirm that Fe, Co, P, O, N and C elements coexist in the MOF on MOF structured nanomaterials (Figs. 1(g)–(m) and Fig. S5). Therefore, it can be determined that FeP-CoP3 has been successfully synthesized with MOF on MOF structure (Fig. S4). The sample FeP-CoP3 was synthesized through three steps, including precursor synthesis, the preparation of precursor using MOF on MOF, and the final material phosphating. Firstly, MIL-88(Fe) will be synthesized under air conditions using a hot stirring method. Then, the Co source was added into the MIL-88(Fe) material using the MOF on MOF synthesis strategy to form the MIL-88(Fe)@ZIF-67 precursor. Finally, PH3 steam is used as the phosphorus source. Phosphating treatment was performed on the precursor to obtain FeP-CoP3 hetero structure (Fig. 2(a) ). To ensure clarity of the sample, it was repeatedly cleaned with hydrochloric acid to remove impurities and purify the FeP-CoP3 catalyzer. According to XRD results (Figs. 2(b) and 2(e)) [27], the sample adopts a low-temperature synthesis process, and the synthesis of the target product can be determined by comparing it with the standard card. According to the intensity of diffraction peaks, the sample contains a large amount of FeP and CoP3 components. The X-ray diffraction peaks of the target sample product appear at 32.7°, 37.2°, 46.3°, 46.9°, 48.3°, and 59.6°, which can be attached to the (011), (111), (202), (211), and (020) crystal planes of the FeP crystal (PDF#78-1443). The XRD peaks at 22.9°, 36.8° and 43.9° can be indexed to (200), (013), and (331) crystal planes (PDF#73-1239) of the CoP3 phase. Comparison samples were prepared by controlling experiments (Figs. 2(c) and 2(d)), CoP3 material was synthesized by phosphating of ZIF-67, and Co3O4 material was fabricated by direct oxidation (PDF#74-1657). FeP was obtained by phosphating MIL-88(Fe), and Fe2O3 was synthesized by further oxidation process (PDF#87-1164). Each sample was matched with the corresponding PDF card. Weak XRD peaks occur at lower synthesis temperatures (400 °C) as a result of lower synthesis temperatures. XRD patterns suggest the successful synthesis of the target catalyst (FeP-CoP3), and characterizing techniques such as Raman spectroscopy, XPS, and TEM were further conducted to confirm the presence of FeP-CoP3. The nitrogen adsorption desorption isotherm is shown in Fig. 2(f), the FeP-CoP3 sample still has a large specific surface area after the phosphorization of the nanoparticles. Simultaneously, as shown in Fig. 2(g), the sample was further analyzed by Raman spectroscopy. It has two distinct peaks at approximately 1359 and 1581 cm−1, indicating disordered carbon (D band) and graphitized carbon (G band), respectively, while an increase in I D/I G values indicates the presence of more defects on the surface, which is more conducive to the catalytic reaction [28,29]. The composition and chemcial states of FeP-CoP3 were explored using XPS. By comparing with the FeP and CoP3 samples (Figs. S8(f) and S9(f)), the superiority of the MOF on MOF preparation process adopted in this study has been further demonstrated. The XPS survey scanning spectrum revealed the existence of Co, Fe, C, N, O, and P elements in the sample (Fig. S6). The binding energy was calibrated using C 1s as a reference. As shown in Fig. S7(b), the three fitted peaks of FeP-CoP3 samples at 284.8, 285.9, and 287.5 eV can be attributed to the C–C, C–N, and C–O bonds of the C species [30]. The overall fitting peak of FeP-CoP3 is similar to that of CoP3 and FeP (Figs. S8(b) and S9(b)), except that the C-N signal is obvious. It can be summarized that the core-shell skeleton contributes to the C–N transfer and thus improves the carbon skeleton behavior. A small amount of N element from cobalt nitrate will form electrophilic carbon atoms and nucleophilic N atoms with the C source in fumaric acid, forming C–N bonds. In Fig. S7(c), the N 1s peak of FeP-CoP3 can be ascribed to pyridine N (399.3 eV), pyrrole N (401.4 eV), and graphite N (407.7 eV) [31]. In fact, graphite he conductivity of carbon skeleton can be enhanced by graphite N. On the other hand, the improvement in its electrocatalytic performance can be attributed to the high binding energy of pyridine N. On the contrary, the pyridine N signal in CoP3 is much weaker (Figs. S8(c) and Fig. S9(c)). Graphitic nitrogen enhances the conductivity of the carbon skeleton, while pyridine nitrogen exhibits the highest binding energy, which makes it easy to enhance its electrocatalytic properties. In contrast, the fitted peak signals of other samples are weaker. In contrast to single FeP and CoP3, due to the interaction of two metal phosphides in FeP-CoP3, the redistribution of orbital electrons in FeP-CoP3 makes it easier to form hydroxyl oxides on the surface that are conducive to electrocatalysis under alkaline conditions. Based on the comparison of element content in Table S1, the sample has a low O content (low oxide content). The XPS peak at 707.1 eV of FeP-CoP3 in Fig. 2(h) is similar to that in FeP. The high-resolution Fe 2p 3/2 XPS spectrum shows three peaks, namely Fe-P, Fe-PO x , and other satellite peaks (Fig. S7(a)) [16,17]. The high-resolution spectrum of Fe 2p indicates that these three peaks are Fe 2p 3/2 (711.6 and 715.7 eV), Fe 2p 1/2 (724.9 and 728.5 eV), and a wobbly satellite peak (730.9 eV). The Fe XPS spectrum of FeP are also consists of Fe 2p 3/2 (711.3 and 713.9 eV), Fe 2p 1/2 (717.4 and 725.1 eV), and wobbly satellite peaks (730.4 eV) (Fig. S8(a)). For Co 2p 3/2 orbit, the XPS peaks can be approximately categorized into three different XPS peaks, which are separately related to Co-P, Co-PO x , and their vibrational satellite peaks (Fig. 2(i)) [32]. The FeP-CoP3 XPS spectrum of Co (Fig. S7(f)) has three XPS peaks including Co–P bonds (779.3 and 792.7 eV), Co–PO x bonds (782.3 and 798.3 eV), and other satellite signals (782.3 and 804.3 eV). The Co peaks of CoP3 (Fig. S9(a)) are separately related to Co–P bonds (781.8 and 788.1 eV), Co–PO x bonds (783.4 and 798.4 eV), and satellite signals (785.3 and 803.4 eV). Sum up, compared with CoP3, the combining energies of Co 2p 3/2 and 2p 1/2 in FeP-CoP3 samples shift to the left side, indicating that the electron cloud density is high, and the electron cloud is more easily polarized when the electrophilic reagent approaches, which helps to generate transition states that are more conducive to the reaction. At the same time, the intermediate ions generated after being attacked by the electrophilic reagent are more stable, and correspondingly, the energy barrier of the reaction transition state is lower, so electrophilic addition is easier to occur [32]. As shown in Fig. 2(j), the P3− metal phosphorus bond at 130 and 134.5 eV belongs to FeP-CoP3 sample (Fig. S7(e)), which might be active center. The peak at 135.2 eV can be attributed to byproducts produced by oxidation on the surface of FeP-CoP3 [19]. The P-XPS spectra of FeP and CoP3 also have three characteristic peaks. Due to exposure to air, there are also oxidized P (PO4 3−) substances on their surfaces (FeP: 134.9 eV; CoP3: 135.7 eV) (Fig. S8(e) and Fig. S9(e)) [19,33–35]. By comparing the three samples, it can be found that due to the positive shift of the Fe orbitals and the negative transformation of the Co orbitals, the P orbitals also undergo a positive shift, resulting in an increase in the valence state of the element and a bias towards the positive polarity of the chemical bonds, thereby freeing up more low state orbitals for electron transfer. The same results still support the support of charge transfer between MOF on MOF nanostructures, thereby enhancing electrocatalytic activity. 3.2 Electrocatalytic hydrogen evolution performance HER performance was evaluated by a standard three electrode apparatus in alkaline solution. The electrocatalytic performances of FeP-CoP3, FeP, Fe2O3, CoP3, Co3O4 electrodes and pure CG were tested and compared. The FeP-CoP3 electrode exhibited extraordinary catalytic activity as shown by the LSV curve (Fig. 3(a) ). The FeP-CoP3 electrode clearly requires Pt-C/CC or zero initial potential (initial potential). The HER performance of the FeP-CoP3 electrode is determined to be 81 mV (η10), 170 mV (η50) and 237 mV (η100) respectively, the electrodes still have advantages at high current densities (Fig. 3c). At a current density of η10, η50 and η100, it outperforms the performance of FeP (113, 203, and 276 mV) and CoP3 (192, 356, and 456 mV). In addition, it can be verified that the performance of FeP-CoP3 electrode in alkaline media is superior to the previously reported materials (Table S2 and Fig. 3(g)). The Tafel slope of the FeP-CoP3 electrode in the Volmer-Tafel mechanism is 71.5 mV dec−1 (Fig. 3(b)), which is much lower than the slope of the FeP electrode (101.5 mV dec−1) and other electrodes. As a result of EIS, reaction kinetics were detected. Compared with other electrodes, the FeP-CoP3 electrode demonstrates significantly lower transfer resistance (R ct = 2 Ω) (Fig. 3(d)), indicating that the MOF on MOF structure can improve the kinetics of charge transfer. Moreover, FeP-CoP3 also exhibits high standardized ESCA activity and has the highest HER performance. The CV curve shows that the FeP-CoP3 electrode has a higher C dl (15.17 mF cm−2) than other samples, indicating that the MOF on MOF structure generates more active sites (Fig. 3(e)). Therefore, this structure can present strong HER performance. Eventually, the electrode (FeP-CoP3) was evaluated using LSV curves and CV cycles (Fig. S10). After CV cycling, the FeP-CoP3 electrode curve clearly shows a slight decrease. Even after 20 h of operation, the decrease in current density is negligible, as shown in the LSV curve of FeP-CoP3 electrode (Fig. 3(h)). The excellent sustainability of FeP-CoP3 has been demonstrated through stability experiments (Fig. 3(f)). After HER testing, SEM and TEM techniques (Fig. S11) were conducted to examine the structural integrity of FeP-CoP3 and found no significant changes in its composition and structure, indicating that reconstruction of the surface of HER is not induced by electrolysis. Therefore, phosphides synthesized from MOF on MOF structure have excellent stability, which is also the main reason for the improving HER performance. 3.3 Electrocatalytic oxygen evolution performance The OER performance of the samples was also investigated. FeP-CoP3 electrode illustrates OER 239 mV (η50), indicating that it also has excellent OER performance (Fig. 4(a) ). Under alkaline medium conditions, the performance of FeP-CoP3 electrode is also superior to the majority of previously reported materials (Table S2 and Fig. 4(g)). As shown in Fig. 4(c), FeP-CoP3 shows lower values of 239 (η50), 263 (η100) and 275 mV (η150), compared to FeP (261, 285, and 298 mV) and CoP3 (267, 292, and 306 mV). Moreover, the FeP-CoP3 electrode shows the best Tafel slope (57.1 mV dec−1), which greatly improves its OER activity. The result indicates that phosphides based on MOF on MOF structure can effectively reduce the energy barrier of electron transfer and promote OER kinetics (Fig. 4(b)). From the CV curve, the FeP-CoP3 electrode (C dl = 15.62 mF cm−2) has better reversible activity than the FeP electrode (C dl = 13.27 mF cm−2). This phenomenon presents that the two coexisting phosphides have higher compatibility, and more active catalytic sites can be generated on the surface (Fig. 4(e) and S12). Detection of reaction kinetics was accomplished using EIS. Compared with other electrodes, the FeP-CoP3 catalyst illustrates significantly lower transfer resistance (R ct = 2 Ω) (Fig. 4(d)), showing that the MOF on MOF structure improves its charge transfer kinetics. In addition, the FeP-CoP3 electrode also has strong consistency in OER performance (Fig. 4(f)). Based on ESCA, the normalized specific activity of FeP-CoP3 is higher than that of FeP and CoP3 (Fig. 4(e) and S13), in the same condition, the TOF value of FeP-CoP3 is also higher than that of other materials (Fig. S14). These findings present that both OER ability and active sites improve with the increase of phosphides. After CV cycling, the current density of FeP-CoP3 catalyst did not significantly decrease (Fig. 4(h)), indicating its unique OER stability. 3.4 Overall water splitting performance Electrolytic cells with dual electrodes were assembled by selecting two identical FeP-CoP3 electrodes. The FeP-CoP3 electrode only requires 1.49 V (η10) to drive the entire water decomposition (Fig. 5(a) and S15). Compared to most reported materials used in alkaline media, this sample presents superior electrocatalytic performance (Table S2 and Fig. 5(d)). After continuous operation at 1.49 V for 40 h, the FeP-CoP3/GC electrode also demonstrates excellent stability with the current decreasing from 10 mA cm−2 to 9.4 mA cm−2 (Fig. 5(b)). During the testing process, the electrocatalytic activity of the electrode briefly declines, nevertheless when 1 mol L−1 NaCl solution is added, the activity eventually stabilizes in simulating seawater conditions. This discovery indicates that the electrode has a certain degree of anti-toxicity (Fig. S16). After achieving all tests, no obvious varieties are found in the XRD pattern (Fig. 5(c)), which further supports the stability of the material (Figs. S17 and S18). Faced to the stability of 94.2% in FeP-CoP3/GC electrode, the comparison samples CoP3 and FeP only achieve 80.5% and 71.6%, which further proves the excellent stability of the composite samples. By analyzing the XPS before and after the sample reaction (Figs. S19 and S20), it was found that the fundamental reason for its performance failure may be related to the surface oxidation of the material. Finally, compared with the reported bifunctional catalysts, the FeP-CoP3 electrode has excellent electrochemical performance in alkaline media (Table S2). 3.5 Electrocatalytic mechanism investigation To demonstrate the excellent electrocatalytic performance of FeP-CoP3 material, DFT calculations were performed. Prior to the calculation, the target sample and control sample were constructed and optimized (Figs. S21 and S22). Typically, ideal HER catalysts have the lowest |ΔG H| values [34,35]. In Fig. 6(a) , the DFT calculation results demonstrate that compared with the control sample, FeP-CoP3 has the lowest |ΔG H| energy (0.12 eV). By calculating and analyzing the adsorption free energies of OH*, OOH*, and O* in the basic process of the structure, DFT method was used to elucidate the potential Co and Fe active sites of the FeP-CoP3 model at different positions in the MOF on MOF structure (Fig. S23). The possibility of Co being the active site is higher for discrete units. The optimized geometric model of FeP-CoP3 for water oxidation process is shown in Fig. S24. Understanding the activity of the entire process in the OER mechanism can be accomplished objectively by utilizing the adsorption energy of intermediates produced from oxygen. It is worth noting that the adsorption capacity and energy barrier of OER intermediate conditions (ΔG) is in inverse proportion [36,37]. The process energy barriers of different materials under different U conditions are shown in Fig. 6. When compared to other materials, it is clear that FeP-CoP3 can successfully alter the four step G values. (Figs. 6(b) and 6(c)). When the applied potential is 1.49 V, the absorption capacity of O * and OH * increases, resulting in a decrease in the ΔG value of FeP-CoP3. The fourth process of CoP3 is the RDS, the conversion of OOH* to O2 has a more high energy barrier of 1.88 eV due to the poor affinity of OOH* intermediates for adsorption on Co sites. However, the RDS energy barrier of FeP-CoP3 decreases to 1.83 eV, demonstrating that the MOF on MOF structure significantly increases OOH* adsorption and lowers the energy threshold. According to all theoretical assessments, MOF on MOF structure can successfully lower the energy barrier for the production of intermediate states, increase OER activity, and improve mass transfer efficiency. These findings are in good agreement with the experimental results. To gain a deeper comprehension of the alterations in electron distribution at the interface between OER intermediates and Co sites throughout the whole OER process [38–40], it is necessary to explore the direction of OOH * electron transfer. Electrons are more likely to move from Fe and P to Co atoms when these two elements coordinate with Co because their electronegativity is lower than Co. The 3D charge density difference plot in Fig. 7(i) further supports this result, where the positive charge of the P atom indicates that Co and Fe can capture electrons during the OER process. More electrons will rise from the metal reaction sites when a MOF on MOF structure forms, drawing higher valence metal species as active sites and speeding up the O2 generation process. Meanwhile, some electrons transfer from metal atoms to the generated OOH*. The d-band centers of the comparative samples of FeP and CoP3, as well as the Fe and Co in the bimetallic phosphide FeP-CoP3, are shown in Figs. 7(a)–(d). It is worth noting that compared to a single phosphide FeP, a rightward vary of the d-band center of Fe atoms can be viewed when CoP3 is added. In the same situation, an obvious rightward shift of the d-band center of Co atoms can also be observed. This phenomenon also illustrates that the significant reaction rate of FeP-CoP3 is closely related to its upgraded adsorption affinity for intermediates. In the OER process, the external conditions of surface-active sites play a crucial role in promoting electron conversion and are largely influenced by their interaction with oxygen-containing intermediates σ the influence of keys. This bonding strength can be accurately analysis by integrating the projected density of states (PDOS) in FeP-CoP3, FeP, and CoP3 into the Fermi energy [39,41]. As is well known, the ƒ e value obtained by projecting the coordination unsaturated state is one of the key parameters for measuring OER activity. The calculated ƒ e values of Fe and Co in bimetallic phosphides FeP-CoP3 and metal atoms in single metal phosphides FeP and CoP3 are determined to be 2.19, 2.45, 4.03, and 4.65, respectively (Figs. 7(e)–(h)). The ultra-high ƒ e causes strong combining between the FeP-CoP3 and oxygen-containing intermediates, resulting in a decrease in catalytic performance. On the contrary, much lower ƒ e can lead to weaken binding, which is also detrimental to catalytic efficiency [41,42]. As a result, having a suitable ƒ e is a key role for improving the catalytic ability. Compared to single metal phosphides FeP and CoP3, bimetallic phosphides FeP-CoP3 exhibit superior catalytic performance (Figs. 7(e)–(h)). For deeper understanding the electrocatalytic mechanism of FeP-CoP3 and analyzing its excellent catalytic performance, corresponding DFT calculations (Figs. 6 and S24) were performed on the target catalyst and other comparison samples. The corresponding results clearly illustrate that Co2+ has more unfilled semi full orbitals compared to Fe3+, indicating a more active interaction between Co and OER intermediates in FeP-CoP3 species. Obviously, after adopting the MOF on MOF structure, the electrons that occupy the P 3p orbital tend to redistribute and accumulate around the Co atom, while there are fewer electrons around the P atom because Co has higher electronegativity, which leads to electron arrangement. It is possible for metal atoms to acquire high valence states due to this property. XPS results show more prominent orbital peaks for Co 2p 3/2 and 2p 1/2, which improves the overall water splitting efficiency. For gaining a deeper learning of the basic principle about metal phosphide center metal improving electrocatalytic performance and combine atomic orbital theory, the electronic configuration of transition metals was studied theoretically [43]. Due to the influence of electron distribution [43,44], the outer electrons of transition metals (Fe and Co) are composed of s-orbital electrons and d-orbital electrons. By visualizing the configuration (arranging the 3d and 4s orbitals in a planar petal shape), the electron distribution of the d orbitals of Fe and Co in transition metals is illustrated (Figs. 8(a) and (b) ), while the bimetallic phosphide FeP-CoP3 constructed based on MOF on MOF is in an ionic state in the reaction (Fig. 8(c)). It can be noted that according to the Hund rule and Pauli Exclusion Principle, the electrons in the outermost d-orbitals of Fe3+ and Co2+ are unpaired, which is more conducive to electron release. Further confirmation shows that compared to single metal phosphides FeP and CoP3, bimetallic phosphides FeP-CoP3 exhibit superior catalytic performance [45]. Experimental data, atomic orbital theory and DFT calculations jointly confirm that metal organic framework metal (MOF on MOF) derived materials exhibit significant heterojunction behavior with a concentration of more significant electron density [46]. This performance profoundly affects the electronic structure of FeP-CoP3, and is also an important manifestation of improving catalyst performance. Specifically, this modulation leads to the formation of coordination unsaturated Co and Fe atoms in the material matrix, which in turn become key sites for oxygen molecule capture, promoting energetically favorable synthesis of O–O bonds, which is a crucial step in OER. Subsequently, the released O* atoms were captured by Co atoms embedded in the FeP-CoP3 lattice [47,48]. By coordinating with adjacent Co atoms, the captured O* atoms exhibit active Co catalytic centers, especially in higher spin electron states. Bader charge analysis supplemented these findings, indicating that throughout the OER process, the Co catalytic center gradually transfers towards a higher oxidation state. The role played in selectively capturing OOH* intermediates from alkaline solutions is attributed to the presence of low-energy 3d orbitals that accommodate unpaired spin electrons. The complex interaction between electronic structure and catalytic behavior highlights the multifaceted properties of MOF on MOF derived materials, promoting the understanding and operation of electrochemical processes in sustainable energy applications. 4 Conclusions In summary, a strategy was proposed to construct two transition metal phosphides into one system (FeP-CoP3) through the MOF on MOF method and promote the activity of bimetallic phosphides. Experimental data, atomic orbital theory and DFT calculations all show that the heterojunction electron density generated by MOF on MOF method is more concentrated, which regulates the electronic structure of FeP-CoP3 and generates coordination unsaturated Co atoms and Fe atoms, thus creating oxygen atom trapping sites for FeP-CoP3 adsorption. FeP-CoP3 is energetically favorable for the binding of O–O bonds, and the dissociated O* atoms are captured by the Co atoms in FeP-CoP3. The captured O* atom coordinates with the surrounding Co atoms, forming a Co catalytic center in higher spin electron states. Bader charge analysis also reveals that the Co catalytic center is formed in a higher oxidation state throughout the entire OER process. Due to the low energy 3d orbitals with unpaired spin electrons, OOH* is captured from alkaline solution. Based on the oxygen atom capture effect, FeP-CoP3 just needs HER 81 mV (η10) overpotential and OER 239 mV (η50) overpotential. When FeP-CoP3 is used for the overall decomposition of water, it demonstrates excellent performance and stability, only requiring 1.49 V (η10) to achieve 10 mA cm−1 current density, and FeP-CoP3 sample presents higher activity under alkaline conditions and demonstrates superior activity among numerous reported catalysts. It is expected that MOF on MOF method can be well combined with other non-precious metal materials. This work provides a novel strategy for creation of cheaply viable bifunctional materials. coredata.dc:description: The electronic modulation characteristics of efficient metal phosphide electrocatalysts can be utilized to tune the performance of oxygen evolution reaction (OER). However, improving the overall water splitting performance remains a challenging task. By building metal organic framework (MOF) on MOF heterostructures, an efficient strategy for controlling the electrical structure of MOFs was presented in this study. ZIF-67 was in-situ synthesized on MIL-88 (Fe) using a two-step self-assembly method, followed by low-temperature phosphorization to ultimately synthesize FeP-CoP3 bimetallic phosphides. By combining atomic orbital theory and theoretical calculations (density functional theory), the results reveal the successful modulation of electronic orbitals in FeP-CoP3 bimetallic phosphides, which are synthesized from MOF on MOF structure. The synergistic impact of the metal center Co species and the phase conjugation of both kinds of MOFs are responsible for this regulatory phenomenon. Therefore, the catalyst demonstrates excellent properties, demonstrating HER 81 mV (η10) in a 1.0 mol L−1 KOH solution and OER 239 mV (η50) low overpotentials. The FeP-CoP3 linked dual electrode alkaline batteries, which are bifunctional electrocatalysts, have a good electrocatalytic ability and may last for 50 h. They require just 1.49 V (η50) for total water breakdown. Through this technique, the electrical structure of electrocatalysts may be altered to increase catalytic activity.
